  "text": "The Kafka log retention policy enforcement is distributed across multiple Java and Scala source files that work together to manage segment deletion based on time and size constraints.\n\n## Core Retention Enforcement (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/UnifiedLog.java)\n\nThe primary enforcement logic resides in UnifiedLog.java, which is the unified log abstraction in Kafka's storage layer. The key method is `deleteOldSegments()` (lines 1894-1902) which orchestrates three types of deletion:\n\n1. **Time-Based Retention**: `deleteRetentionMsBreachedSegments()` (lines 1908-1944) - Deletes segments based on their timestamp. For each segment, it checks if `currentTime - segment.largestTimestamp() > retentionMs`. The method logs the deletion reason using either the largest record timestamp or the last modified time of the segment. It respects the `localRetentionMs` configuration for remote-enabled setups.\n\n2. **Size-Based Retention**: `deleteRetentionSizeBreachedSegments()` (lines 1946-1975) - Enforces log size limits by calculating if `logSize > retentionSize`. It iteratively removes segments until the log size falls below the configured retention size. Uses `localRetentionSize()` for remote storage scenarios. The method tracks remaining bytes to delete in an AtomicLong.\n\n3. **Log Start Offset-Based Deletion**: `deleteLogStartOffsetBreachedSegments()` (lines 1977-1998) - Removes segments that are entirely before the log start offset. This is particularly important for remote storage scenarios where segments may have been uploaded and deleted from remote storage, requiring local segment cleanup.\n\n## Configuration Management (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/LogConfig.java)\n\nLogConfig.java defines the configuration properties with their validators:\n\n- Line 161: `LOG_RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG` - Server-side config for maximum log size\n- Line 201-202: `RETENTION_MS_CONFIG` - Topic-level config for time-based retention (with validation allowing negative values)\n- Lines 244-247: Remote storage retention configs - `LOCAL_LOG_RETENTION_MS_CONFIG` and `LOCAL_LOG_RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG`\n- Lines 266-267: Public fields `retentionSize` and `retentionMs` for accessing configuration values\n- Lines 409-415: Methods `localRetentionMs()` and `localRetentionBytes()` that provide effective retention values accounting for remote storage settings\n\nThe RemoteLogConfig inner class (lines 65-91) manages the complexity of local vs. remote retention with default values of -2 indicating \"use server-wide defaults\".\n\n## Configuration Constants (server-common/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/server/config/ServerLogConfigs.java)\n\nServerLogConfigs.java defines all broker-level retention configuration constants:\n\n- Lines 57-62: `LOG_RETENTION_TIME_MILLIS_CONFIG`, `LOG_RETENTION_TIME_MINUTES_CONFIG`, `LOG_RETENTION_TIME_HOURS_CONFIG` - Time-based retention with documentation\n- Lines 64-66: `LOG_RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG` with default of -1 (unlimited)\n- Lines 68-70: `LOG_CLEANUP_INTERVAL_MS_CONFIG` - The retention check interval (default 5 minutes) that controls how often garbage collection runs\n- Line 69: Default check interval is 5 * 60 * 1000L milliseconds\n\n## Log Manager Orchestration (core/src/main/scala/kafka/log/LogManager.scala)\n\nThe Scala LogManager class orchestrates retention checks:\n\n- Lines 62-80: Constructor receives `retentionCheckMs` parameter (line 71) which determines how frequently `deleteOldSegments()` is called\n- Lines 1404-1410: The garbage collection loop calls `log.deleteOldSegments()` on all logs, including future logs\n- The LogManager schedules periodic cleanup tasks using the Scheduler component\n\n## Dynamic Configuration Validation (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/DynamicBrokerConfig.scala)\n\nDynamicBrokerConfig.scala validates the interaction between local and remote retention settings:\n\n- Lines 664-677: `validateLogLocalRetentionMs()` - Ensures local retention milliseconds are properly configured when remote log storage is enabled, preventing invalid configurations where local retention exceeds global retention\n- Lines 679-692: `validateLogLocalRetentionBytes()` - Similar validation for size-based retention, ensuring `logLocalRetentionBytes <= logRetentionBytes`\n\n## Broker Configuration Validation (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/KafkaConfig.scala)\n\nKafkaConfig.scala performs static validation of retention settings:\n\n- Line 508: Validates `logRetentionTimeMillis >= 1 or logRetentionTimeMillis == -1` (unlimited), ensuring retention time is either positive or explicitly unlimited\n\n## Remote Storage Retention (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/server/log/remote/storage/RemoteLogManager.java)\n\nThe RemoteLogManager handles retention for remote-stored segments:\n\n- Lines 1125-1129: `RemoteLogRetentionHandler` constructor receives optional `RetentionSizeData` and `RetentionTimeData` objects\n- Lines 1131-1152: `isSegmentBreachedByRetentionSize()` - Enforces size-based retention by tracking remaining breached bytes and marking segments for deletion\n- Lines 1154-1171: `isSegmentBreachedByRetentionTime()` - Enforces time-based retention by comparing segment's `maxTimestampMs` against retention cutoff time\n- Lines 2159-2171: `RetentionSizeData` class validates that `remainingBreachedSize > 0` when exceeding size limits\n\n## Segment Deletion Mechanics (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/LocalLog.java and SegmentDeletionReason.java)\n\nThe actual segment deletion is handled by:\n\n- `removeAndDeleteSegments()` method in LocalLog.java (lines 389-402) - Takes a collection of segments to delete and processes them\n- `SegmentDeletionReason` interface (lines 22-24 of SegmentDeletionReason.java) - Provides reason tracking for deletion operations\n\n## Summary\n\nThe log retention policy enforcement in Apache Kafka operates through a coordinated pipeline:\n\n1. **Configuration Definition**: ServerLogConfigs defines the `log.retention.ms`, `log.retention.bytes`, and `log.retention.check.interval.ms` properties\n2. **Configuration Storage**: LogConfig loads and validates these settings, managing both broker-wide and per-topic configurations\n3. **Validation**: DynamicBrokerConfig and KafkaConfig validate retention settings at configuration time\n4. **Orchestration**: LogManager schedules periodic cleanup tasks based on the retention check interval\n5. **Enforcement**: UnifiedLog implements three complementary deletion strategies (time-based, size-based, and offset-based) that work together\n6. **Remote Storage**: RemoteLogManager extends the enforcement to remote-stored segments with specialized retention logic\n7. **Execution**: LocalLog and SegmentDeletionReason handle the actual file deletion and reason tracking\n\nThis multi-layered approach ensures robust enforcement of both time-based and size-based retention policies while supporting advanced scenarios like tiered storage."
